{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254711/1930070501/0435.xml":{"full_text":"Market Faces Real Test; Bulls Point to Signs of Technical Improvement\nTHISWEEK\u2019S\nRALLIES NOT\nIMPRESSIVE\nFirmer Commodity Prices and\nBond Market Rally to Give\nFirst Signs of Trade Boom\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nNEW YORK, July s.\u2014Another\nsevere test is in store for the\nstock market next week, accord\ning to market observers who have\nusually been accurate in their\nprognostications in the financial\ndistrict. This week s rally, accord\ning to these experts, was but a\ntechnical rally in a bear market,\nliquidation in the meantime hav\ning dried up by reason of the\nabsence of selling pressure in a\nholiday week.\nAt Thursday\u2019s close the gen\neral average of 90 representative\nstocks was up only 6\u2019/ 2 points\nfrom the low of the year, and\nshowed a 45-point shrinkage from\nthe April peak. The industrials\nhad rallied only 7 points and\nfrom a 53-point shrinkage and\nutilities had recovered but 10\npoints of a 77-point decline.\nLoans Drag\nMeanwhile the bulls point con\nfidently to the cumulative evi\ndences of a technical improve\nment in the market. Thursday\u2019s\nReserve Board figures showed a\nnew decrease of $197,000,000 in\nbrokers\u2019 loans, bringing the total\nto less than the volume of Au\ngust, 1927. Few of the market\nobservers who are now talking\nlower prices have in all prob\nability taken cognizance of that\nfact.\nThere is also the fact that\nstockholders\u2019 lists of the big cor\nporations are steadily expanding,\nwhile deflation of commodity\nvalues as well as of extravagant\nspeculative ideas has been pro\nceeding at a good gait. Firming\ncommodity prices and a genuine\nrally in the bond market will\ngive the first reliable clues to the\nbusiness revival. Accumulation of\ngood stocks should not be de\nlayed much beyond the time\nwhen these indications unmistak\nably appear.\nInvestment Trust Buying\nMuch has been said of the po\nsition which the investment trust\nplays in the market, but whether\nor not it acts as an important aid\nor deterrent to price movement is\na question that has not been sat\nisfactorily decided. It cannot be\ngainsaid, however, that the im\nportant investment trust is in a\nposition to note the constantly\nchanging developments in various\ncompanies and act upon them\nsooner than the average investor\nor trader. In this respect, it is in\nteresting to note, the changes that\nhave been made in the holdings\nof the Lehman Corporation, spon\nsored by one of Wall Street\u2019s lead\ning banking houses, in the period\nbetween December 31 and June 30.\nCommon stocks that appear in\nthe portfolio for the first time in\nclude 20,000 shares of American\nRadiator and Standard Sanitary,\n46,000 shares of General Foods.\n30,000 J. C. Penney, 32,000 Radio,\nand smaller blocks of Associated\nDry Goods, Coca-Cola. Colgate\nPalmolive Peet. Hahn Department\nStores. Liggett Myers B, Para\nmount Publix, Pure Oil, Anaconda\nand Kennecott.\nCommon stocks whose holdings\nwere substantially h creased in\nclude Kroger Grocery, from 18,-\nOOC to 50,000; National Dairy,\nfrom 21,000 to 30.000. and -Inter\nnationtl Nickel, from 20,000 to\n60,000. and lesser changes in Air\nReduction, American Can. Macy,\nNational Biscuit, Radio-Keith.\nUnion Carbide, Westinghouse\nElectric, American Telephone and\nTelegraph, Electric Bond and\nShare, Electric Power and Light,\nPacific Lighting, Humble Oil.\nStandard Oil of Indiana, Commer\ncial Investment Trust and Corn\nProducts.\nHoldings were reduced in Gen\neral Electric, Eastman Kodak\nConsolidated Gas. Pacific Gas\nPublic Service of New\nUnited Gas Improvement, Con\ntinental Oil. Gulf Oil and Stand\nard Oil of New Jersey.\nw. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\nM EMBER S\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew Ydrk Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nHIBBS'BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nWASHINGTON TIMESII FINANCIAL NEWS\nj Leader\nr '.V'-\njg\n\u2014Photo by International\nJOHN L. LEWIS\nPRESIDENT OF the United\nMine Workers, who is expected\nto take his place at the head\nof the miners delegation in the\nconference between operators\nand workers. The conference\nwill be resumed Monday in New\nYork wnere knotty problems\nconfronting both sides are ex\npected to be speeded up by the\nminer\u2019s president.\nffIOISBONOS\nPUT ON SALE\nPublic offering is being made by\nHalsey, Stuart and Company of\nan issue of $15,000,000 Public\nService Company of Northern\nIllinois first lien and refunding\nmortgage 4Mi per cent bonds.\nSeries E. due July 1, 1980. at 94\nand interest, yielding about 4.82\nper cent.\nThe company serves 316 com\nmunities located in a compact\narea of Illinois, embracing the\nwealthy suburban territory tribu\ntary to Chicago and the surround\ning widely diversified manufactur\ning and agricultural districts.\nElectric service is rendered in Sl4\ncommunities, gas in 102, water in\n5 and heat in 3.\nThe bonds precede $20,000,000\nprincipal amount of 5 per cent\ndebentures, 100,000 shares of out\nstanding preferred stock paying $6\nper share per annum, 63,576 shares\nof outstanding preferred stock\npaying $7 per share per annum\nand 454,632 shares of outstanding\ncommon stock paying $8 per share\nper annum, all having a combined\nmarket value as indicated by re\ncent quotations of over $161,000.-\n000. In addition. 48,010 shares of\ncommon stock have been sold at\npayments which should be com\npleted from time to time prior to\nAugust 2. 1930.\nFor the 12 months ended De\ncember 31 last, gross revenues (in\ncluding other income) was $34.-\n843.712; operating expenses, in\ncluding maintenance, taxes and\nrents (but not including deprecia\ntion. amortization of debt dis\ncount, etc.). $20,213,218, and net\nearnings, $14,630,494.\nTimes Souare Trust\nCapital Cut Voted\nStockholders of the Times\nSquare Trust Co. ratified the pro\nposal to reduce the capital stock\nfrom $2,000,000 to $1,000,000, re\nleasing $1,000,000 for surplus. The\nchange gives the bank the fol\nlowing capital structure: Capital.\n$1,000,000: surplus, $1,000,000. and\nreserve for all contingencies,\n$467,293. A reduction in the par\nvalue of the bank\u2019s shares from\nSIOO to S2O and an increase in\nthe number of shares to 50,000,\ngiving present stockholders 2*/4\nshares of the new par value stock\nfor each old share held, were\nvoted.\n\u201cIt Is the opinion of the\nboard the acquisition of one or\nmore banks by absorption or\nmerger will become more logical\nand negotiations leading thereto\nmay be promptly consum\nmated,\u2019* Harry H. Reyman,\nchairman of the board, said.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nM.K.T; LOADINGS\nSHDWIOP.G.\nINCREASE\nOfficials Expect Gains Over\nMay To Be Continued; New\nExpress Service Is Installed\nAn estimated increase of 10\nper cent in June car loadings\ncompared with those of May was\nannounced yesterday by New\nYork officers of the Missouri,\nKansas and Texas Railroad Com\npany. The gain is attributed to\nthe wheat movement which be\ngan June 16, to the hauling of\nlarge quantities of cement for use\nin road building in Oklahoma\nand Texas, and the transporta\ntion of steel pipe to be used in\nthe gas pipe lines running out of\nTexas into the Middle West.\nCompared with June, 1929, car\nloadings on the road show a\ndecrease of 9.3 per cent for June,\nthe figures being 45,849 cars in\nJune last year, against 41,933\nin June this year. In the week\nended June 28, 1930, cars to the\nnumber of 10,446 were loaded,\ncompared with 11,781 in the cor\nresponding week of 1929.\nNotwithstanding the decline\nfrom June a year ago, road offi\ncials expect the present trend of\nimprovement to continue. It is\nthought that wheat will move in\nvolume notwithstanding low\nprices and the over plus now in\nstorage, as many farmers in the\nroad\u2019s territory are not in finan\ncial position to hold the crop.\nFreight-Express Service\nFreight-express service '\u2019supple\nmental to the regular less than\nearload service of the Missouri,\nKansas and Texas lines has just\nbeen instituted in Texas through\nthe agency of the Missouri, Kan\nsas and Texas Transportation\nCompany. By means of this\nagency shippers are provided\nwith a pickup and delivery sys\ntem of freight handling not hith\nerto afforded them. The trans\nportation company is owned by\nthe railroad company and offi\ncered by the M. K. T. officials.\nUnder the Katy freight-express\nservice plan there is no operation\nof motor trubeks on the highways\nby the transportation company.\nThe railroad company contracts\nwith the transportation company\nto perform the pickup and de\nlivery part of the service, and\nthe transportation company in\nturn contracts with existing dray\nor transfer lines in the com\nmunities served to pick up out\nbound freight and bring it to\nthe railroad station and to de\nliver inbound freight to the con\nsignees. Thus there is no dupli\ncation of existing service, but a\nco-ordination in the direction of\nmore efficient service. Store door\ndelivery service is thereby pro\nvided without the addition of\nmore motor trucks.\nChief field of operation of the\nnew service at the outset is from\nDallas and Ft. Worth to Wichita\nFalls, from Ft. Worth to Denison\nand Dallas to Denison via Green\nville, from Dallas and Ft. Worth\nto Temple, and between San An\ntonio and Smithville and Hous\nton and Smithville. The railroad\npart of the new service will be\nhandled in its present package\ncars.\nThe chief purpose of instituting\nthis new service through the Mis\nsouri, Kansas Texas Transpor\ntation Co., is to preserve and ex\ntend the present less carload ser\nvice of the railroad company.\nInitially, this service is confined\nto 27 of the larger Texas com\nmunities served by the Katy, but\nthe tariffs of the transportation\ncompany are so devised that the\nservice can be extended to other\ncommunities as desired\nEquipment Good\nIt is the present purpose of\nthe railroad company to confine\nits activities of this character\nto the State of Texas, but if\nconditions make necessary or de\nsirable the company is prepared\nto extend the service to Missouri,\nKansas and Oklahoma, the other\nStates served by M.-K.-T. Lines.\nThe Commercial\nNational Bank\n14TH AND G STS. N. W.\nLet ue eupply your vacation\nnetdt of Traveler!' Check!\nand Letter* of Credit.\nProtect Your Valuables\nRent a Safe Deposit Box in\nour burglar and fireproof\nvaults.\nDeposit your reserve in a\nsavings account bearing in\nterest on daily balances.\nMAKE YOUR WILL\nName This Bank as\nYour Executor.\nI\nThe Bank of Personal\nService.\nWade H. Cooper, President\n\u201cBusiness as Usual\u201d\nAir Marks Industry\nFor Coming Season\nBy JOHA E. NEVIN, Jr.\nA \u2018\u2018business as usual\u201d atmos-\nphere is confidently anticipated I\nto permeate the industrial world\nfrom now on. With the ending\nof the Fourth of July rest period,\nthe so-called \u201cset holiday season\u201d\nis out of the way until Septem\nber.\nCongress has folded its tent and\ngone home. The great July com\nmittments are taken care of.\nEnormous public works planned\nare to be pushed throughout the\ncountry, but especially here in\nthe National Capital. The out\ncome. according to the leaders in\nfinancial and industrial circles\nhere, must be most beneficial.\nHeat Effect Nil\nThis, too, in the face of the I\n\u2018\u2018dog days\u201d season. There seems\nto be a general acceptance here\nthat the torrid months that the\ncountry now faces will have less\neffect on business generally than\nin recent years.\nThe chief reason assigned to\nthis by the experts is that the\nmonths of deflation and the\nstages of uncertainty which\ni marked the last few weeks of the\ntariff fight brought general busi\nness to a stage which compelled\nmerchants to let their stocks run\ndown to a low level, with the in\nevitable result that the consuming\npublic did without much that was\nneeded. Now the public is ex\npected to stock up and their dol\nlars, thus thrown into the market,\nwill boost trade in every line.\nSales Slated\nThe larger business establish\nments of Washington have made\nBaltimore Produce\nApplpn\u2014Supply Tnodtmtw: Maryland\nand Virginia bushel basket Transparent*,\naa tn \u00abiz#\u00bb. St\u00a9?, various other early\nvarieties, 1 25; bush*! hampers,\nvarious early varieties. 400 75n.\nAsparagus\u2014Supply light. Doxen bunch\ncrates *re*n. large, $3 03.50 few higher,\nmedium $202.50; small. $0.750 125.\nRea ns\u2014Supply moderate. Nearby, per\nbushel, round atringless. Bounti\nful*. 35 0 50c.\nBeet*\u2014Supply moderate. Nearby per\nbunch, 1 ft 2c.\nBlack light. New Jer\nsey, 16 01 Sc quart. Eastern Shore, Mary\nland and nearby. ll@lSc.\nCabbage\u2014Supply moderate. Nearby\nI\u2019s-buthel hampers Wakefield. 40065 C;\nbushel baskets, round type. 60 075 c.\nCantaloupe*\u2014Two Arizona, two Cali\nfornia. one South Carolina arrived. 12\ncars track, including broken. Supp\u2019y\nmoderate, demand moderate, market\nabout steady. California Perfectos,\njumbo 455. $5.2505 50. Standard 455,\n$4.7505; pony 45s and 54a. $303.50,\nArizona. Yuma district, Salmon Tints,\njumbo 455. $5 2505.50; jumbo 365. $5;\nstandard 455, $4.50; jumbd flats. 9* and\n12s. $1.90; standard flats, 12s and 7 ss,\n$1.75. Honey Dews: One California ar\nrived. Seven cars track. including\nhrokne. Supply moderate, demand slow,\nmarket weak. California standard\ncrates, all sixes, mostly $2.50. Haney\nRalls\u2014no carlot arrivals, nn cars track.\nSupply light, demand moderate; market\ndull. California jumho 45s mostly $6;\nstandard 455, $4.75; pony 45s and 545,\n$3.5004.\nCarrots\u2014Supply moderate. California\nwestern lettuce crate?, bunched, best\n$2.7503; poorer. $202.5